<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>The Graph of <m>\tan(\theta)</m></title>
<p>
    In the axes below: sketch a graph of <m>y = \tan(\theta)</m>
</p>
 <image>   
<prefigure label = "tangent" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(600,250)" margins="(30,5,30,5)">
  <coordinates bbox="(-2*pi-.2, -6, 2*pi+.2, 6)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="\theta"
               h-pi-format="yes"
               hticks="(-2*pi,pi/4,2*pi)"
               hlabels="(-2*pi,pi/2,2*pi)"            
               spacings="((-2*pi,pi/4,2*pi),(-6,1,6))"/>
  </coordinates>
</diagram> 
</prefigure>
</image>  

</paragraphs>   

<paragraphs>
    <title>Formula for Transformation of <m>\tan(\theta)</m></title>
<p>
    Use graphical transformations of the graph of <m>y = \tan(\theta)</m> to find a formula for the function whose graph is shown below.
</p>
 <image>   
<prefigure label = "tangent-transform" xmlns="https://prefigure.org">
<diagram dimensions="(600,250)" margins="(30,5,30,5)">
  <definition>f(x)=5*tan(4*x)+10</definition>
  <coordinates bbox="(-pi/2-.2, -20, pi/2+.2, 30)">
    <grid-axes xlabel="\theta"
               h-pi-format="yes"
               hticks="(-2*pi,pi/16,2*pi)"
               hlabels="(-2*pi,pi/4,2*pi)"            
               spacings="((-2*pi,pi/8,2*pi),(-20,5,30))"/>
    <graph function="f"/>
  </coordinates>
</diagram> 
</prefigure>
</image>  
    
</paragraphs>

</page>

<page>

<paragraphs>
    <title>Relations with Sine and Cosine</title>
    <p>
        Using the relationships between the sine, cosine, and tangent functions, when we are given the value of one of the three functions and a quadrant, we can find the other two.
    </p>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p workspace="3.5in">
                Suppose <m>\theta</m> is an angle in quadrant II with <m>\cos(\theta) = -\frac{3}{4}</m>. Find the values of <m>\sin(\theta)</m> and <m>\tan(\theta)</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
        <li>
            <p workspace="3.5in">
                Suppose <m>\theta</m> is an angle in quadrant I with <m>\tan(\theta) = \frac{x}{4}</m>. Find the values of <m>\sin(\theta)</m> and <m>\cos(\theta)</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>

</paragraphs>



